{{bilateral|Maltese-Spanish|Malta|Spain}}
{{More citations needed|date=May 2015}}
'''Malta–Spain relations''' refer to foreign relations between [[Malta]] and [[Spain]].  Both countries established mutual diplomatic relations in 1977 {{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}.  Malta has an embassy in [[Madrid]] and 5 honorary consulates (in [[Barcelona]], [[Palma de Mallorca]], [[Santander, Cantabria|Santander]], [[Seville]] and [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]]). Spain has an embassy in [[Ta' Xbiex]]<ref>http://www.malta.com/en/local-information/public-service/embassy/spain</ref> and Cultural Centre in [[Balzan]].<ref>http://www.spanishmaltesecentre.org/about/</ref>
Both countries are full members of the [[European Union]] and of the [[Union for the Mediterranean]].

==Migration issues==
[[File:Villa_Macedonia_-_Embassy_of_Spain_in_Malta.jpeg|thumb|right|Villa Macedonia, Cultural Centre of Hispanic-Maltese (relations) at [[Balzan]]]]
In December 2008, the two countries agreed to collaborate on issues relating to illegal migration, including repatriation. In a meeting between Home Affairs Minister [[Carmelo Mifsud Bonnici]] and his Spanish counterpart [[Alfredo Perez Rubalcaba]], they agreed that the implementation of the Immigration and Asylum Pact was a priority. The two countries agreed that a group of Spanish police should be sent to Malta in 2009 to help the Maltese force with repatriation.
<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20081212/local/malta-spain-to-collaborate-in-the-repatriation-of-illegal-migrants |title=Malta, Spain to collaborate in the repatriation of illegal migrants |publisher=Timesofmalta.com |date=2008-12-12 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>

==Agreements==
In January 2007, the two countries entered into a tax treaty.<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-152959338.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103011514/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-152959338.html |date=November 3, 2012 }}</ref>

